"When we got there, he put on some music, and he said, “The custom is to observe silence.” So I knew I wasn’t supposed to talk. I didn’t know at the time, but we were listening to the chanting of Maria Sabina, the Mazatec shaman. I think it was very moving, and we sat wrapped up in blankets by the fireplace. His daughter, who was a Ph.D. in nursing, sat in the corner as the monitor in case anything went wrong."⁣
⁣
More of this conversation can be watched via my YouTube channel. Click the link in my bio.⁣
⁣
Recorded 05/14/21.

Do not do what you hate.⁣
⁣
I don't mean don't do difficult things. I mean, watch your behaviour. If you're doing things that make you hate yourself, then consider the cost of continuing.⁣
⁣
From my podcast with @AubreyMarcus - 03/10/21.

#JordanPeterson #Responsibility #Psychology #MentalHealth

node.text:
What is the antidote to the suffering and malevolence of life? The highest possible goal.

What is the prerequisite to the pursuit of the highest possible goal? The willingness to adopt the maximum degree of responsibility.

You might object: “Why should I shoulder all that burden? It is nothing but sacrifice, hardship, and trouble.” But what makes you so sure you do not want something heavy to carry? You positively need to be occupied with something weighty, deep, profound, and difficult.

Your life becomes meaningful in precise proportion to the depths of the responsibility you are willing to shoulder.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Jordan B. Peterson on August 05, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of one or more people, people playing musical instruments and indoor.

node.text:
What do you do if you're afraid and, to some degree, anxious?

You lay out what you're anxious about in detail. Ask yourself, "What it is that I'm afraid of that might happen?" Next, you deconstruct it into smaller increments - into hypothetically manageable problems - and then you expose yourself, gradually, to the thing that you're afraid of.

The effect of this is not that you become less afraid. What happens instead? You become braver. And that's not the same thing.

It's not like, "well, the world isn't as dangerous as I thought it was, you know, silly me." What happens, realistically, is, "yeah, the damn world's just as dangerous as I thought, or maybe it's even more dangerous than I thought. It turns out that there's something in me that responds to taking that on as a voluntary challenge and grows and thrives as a consequence."

To decide to move forward courageously into the land of the unknown. That's one of the secrets to a good life.

Why are weak people such a problem?⁣
⁣
There's a variety of reasons. First of all, if you can't support your own weight, that means somebody else has to. Then, if you don't pick a forthright, useful, and noble pathway through life, you will become bitter and resentful.⁣
⁣
And once that happens, you'll begin to seek your revenge on the world.⁣
⁣
That's not good.⁣
⁣
From my interview with @FredrikSkavlan in October 2018.

node.text:
Anxiety isn't just an unpleasant psychological state. You're revved up. And you're burning resources like mad.

"I don't know where I am" means everything around you is relevant, and you have to ramp up your capacity for action to deal with that.

We structure almost all of our environments constantly. We're all dressed the same, with tiny variations, and we all follow the same traffic laws, for example. We do everything we can to make sure that we know exactly where we are and what we're doing all the time.

Because when we're in that state, we can advance cautiously using positive things and maintain a modicum of positive emotion.

That's what we're trying to do.
